Sure, I can help you write a basic function to convert markdown to HTML. However, please note that markdown can be quite complex and this function will only handle a few basic cases like headings, paragraphs, and links. For a full-featured markdown to HTML converter, you might want to use an existing library like `markdown` or `pandoc`.

Here's a simple function that converts a subset of markdown to HTML:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <sstream>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(std::string &markdown) {
    std::stringstream html;
    std::string line;
    std::regex headingRegex("^#{1,6} .*");
    std::regex linkRegex("\\[([^\\[]+)\\]\\(([^\\)]+)\\)");

    while (std::getline(markdown, line)) {
        if (std::regex_match(line, headingRegex)) {
            int level = 0;
            while (line[level] == '#') {
                level++;
            }
            line.erase(0, level);
            html << "<h" << level << ">" << line << "</h" << level << ">\n";
        } else {
            std::string::size_type start = 0;
            while ((start = line.find("[", start)) != std::string::npos) {
                std::string linkText = "";
                std::string linkUrl = "";
                std::smatch match;
                if (std::regex_search(line.begin() + start, line.end(), match, linkRegex)) {
                    linkText = match[1].str();
                    linkUrl = match[2].str();
                    line.replace(start, match.length(), "<a href=\"" + linkUrl + "\">" + linkText + "</a>");
                    start += linkText.length() + linkUrl.length() + 13; // 13 is the length of "<a href=""></a>"
                } else {
                    break;
                }
            }
            html << "<p>" << line << "</p>\n";
        }
    }

    return html.str();
}
```

This function handles headings (up to 6 levels deep) and links. It doesn't handle other markdown features like bold text, italic text, lists, images, etc.

